@inproceedings{Ji2009aa,
	Abstract = {Covert channels are widely used for secret information transmission on networks. Although packet length based covert channels have greatly enhanced tamper resistance, they are still vulnerable to detections due to abnormal network traffic. Thus, in this paper, we are motivated to design a novel protocol-independent covert channel that could deliver normal network traffic. We simulated our covert channel on HTTP protocol and analyzed its security and bandwidth.},
	Address = {Piscataway, NJ, USA},
	Annote = {- Taking network protocols as carriers, covert channel has recently been widely applied for covert communication on networks. 
- Network covert channels hide the secret communication into normal network traffic to resist detection.
- There are many notable methods to design network covert channel in literature. 
- One important branch is to use packet length. 
- Padlipsky and Girling proposed to use the length of link layer frames directly. 
- Yao proposed another covert channel called LAWB based on the packet length. 
- Such covert channels based on packet length could enhance tamper resistance. 
- However, they are still vulnerable to detections due to the abnormal network traffic.
- In this paper, we propose a novel protocol-independent network covert channel based on message length. 
- In covert transmission, each message learns from the Reference to get the similar length distribution. 
- As such, the length distribution of our resulting messages is very similar to that of normal network messages.
- Packet length based methods are an important branch of covert channel design, for the reason that they could resist attacks that modify the fields of transmitting packets.
- Padlipsky and Girling proposed to modulate the length of link layer frames for secret message transmission.
- The secret message is made up of several bytes. 
- Each byte is represented by a certain frame length. 
- The method employs 256 different frame lengths to describe the bytes. 
- The receiver deduces the bytes of the secret message through the frames sending to him. 
- In this method, the secret message is usually encrypted, resulting in random bytes of message content, which leads to the random frame length distribution.
- Yao proposed another model based on packet length, named LAWB. 
- The sender and receiver share a secret matrix, with each cell representing a unique length. 
- Let us denote the byte of the secret message to be sent as i. 
- The sender randomly chooses an element len from the ith row of the secret matrix and sends out a packet of length len. 
- After receiving the packet, the receiver scans the matrix to locate which row the element len lies in, so as to get the byte i. 
- After sending several bytes of the secret message, the sender and receiver would do some matrix transformation simultaneously. 
- The above process is repeated until the whole secret message has been transmitted.
- Along with packet length based methods, there also exist some methods based on unused bits field and Initial Sequence Number (ISN).
- Then Alice and Bob would take the following five steps to transmit the secret message:
Step 1: Alice and Bob communicate normally. They both record the message lengths sent by Alice, and make the record as Reference.
Step 2: Alice and Bob select a length l from the Reference by the same random algorithm.
Step 3: In the ith sending, Alice sends to Bob a message of length lnext=l+SUMi. The Reference is updated by appending lnext.
Step 4: Bob decodes the ith message into Wi by subtracting l from lnext.
Step 5: Steps 2 to 4 are repeated until the whole secret message has been sent.
Notes:
(1) k, w and n are shared by Alice and Bob.
(2) Let max_L be the maximum message length in the initial Reference, then max_L>2w should be satisfied.
(3) In Step 3, if lnext < 0, lnext = lnext + max_L.},
